The paper deals with the problem of constructing geometric spanners in high dimensions, which is a fundamental problem in computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also presents an efficient algorithm for constructing spanners, which involves data structures and algorithms, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) another likely sub-category. The paper also involves graph theory and combinatorics, making cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.DC (Discrete Computational Geometry) possible sub-categories. Finally, the paper deals with the problem of fault-tolerant spanners, which involves graph theory and fault-tolerant computing, making cs.GR (Computer Science and Game Theory) a possible sub-category as well.
